<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; IF YOU WANT TO FOLLOW THIS LEADER, JUST SNIFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH TOSCHES, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mao Tse-Tung -- the spelling of whose name was later changed to Mao Zedong, 
forcing the world's comedians to make fairly significant changes in numerous 
punch lines -- overcame peasant status to march across China, overthrow the 
Nationalists, then rule a massive nation for nearly three decades. 
</P>
<P>
 All this from an overweight man with green teeth who never bathed and who, 
into his 80s, spent much of his time rolling around naked with young women. 
That latter habit earned him the affectionate nickname Sunkuotang Jianxgi 
Miuxtin ("Bob Barker of China.") 
</P>
<P>
 These and other startling and stomach-churning revelations about the communist 
giant are courtesy Li Zhisui, Mao's personal physician for 22 years. Li seldom 
left Mao's side, which, by the way, tended to be the upwind side. 
</P>
<P>
 Li now lives in Chicago and has written a book about the unbathed leader, a 
book initially titled, "Twenty-Two Years With a Clothespin on My Nose" but 
changed at the last minute to "The Private Life of Chairman Mao." 
</P>
<P>
 In those 22 years, Li claims, Mao never once bathed. He also refused to brush 
his teeth, and years before his death the choppers had turned a lovely 
turquoise from decay. When the doctor begged Mao to brush, he replied, "A tiger 
never brushes his teeth." 
</P>
<P>
 Li seemingly did not want to risk being disciplined by suggesting that Mao did 
not resemble a tiger but rather a bloated water buffalo, and opted for the more 
simple response of, "You betcha, Boss!" 
</P>
<P>
 Li says Mao spent years without even leaving his bed, a monstrous piece of 
furniture that was carried about the country -- with the happy-go-lucky leader 
under the sheets -- by legions of strong men. Strong enough, in fact, to be 
able to hoist the Honorable Load with just one hand, the other needed, of 
course, to pinch their nostrils shut. Most dreaded by these servants was not 
war or famine or even a bloody counterrevolution, but rather an unexpected gust 
of wind that would sweep the Supreme Stench over them. 
</P>
<P>
 So, you're probably wondering how the heck did an aging man who smelled like 
the rear ends of a thousand panda bears and had mushrooms growing from his 
mouth do so well with the babes? 
</P>
<P>
 Well, experts have suggested it was the Chairman's magnificent personality and 
overwhelming aura of sexuality. Of course, others have suggested that perhaps 
his fanatical, billion-man army may have contributed -- at least in some small 
way. 
</P>
<P>
 Throughout his reign, not a single account was written of even one teen-age 
target of Mao's great lust telling him: "Not tonight, I have a headache. And 
more to the point, my teal-toothed Great Communist Landfill, you give off 
unspeakable odor." 
</P>
<P>
 Not one! 
</P>
<P>
 Mao's particular bell-ringer was a bout with four or five girls at the same 
time -- the girls were ordered to exclaim "Papa Oom Mao, Mao!" at frequent 
intervals -- which he claimed was the only way to restore his "declining yang," 
in Li's words. To be able to restore this yang (I think we should be careful 
here not to overuse the word yang ) for hours at a time without stopping, Mao 
was often forced to think about baseball. Or, as a last resort, about his own 
teeth. 
</P>
<P>
 The rampant sexuality, Li says, was Mao's attempt to copy China's legendary 
first emperor, a man said to have achieved immortality by making love to 1,000 
virgins. Chinese legend also has it that this emperor took a lot of naps. He 
lives still, the story goes, roaming the Chinese countryside with a big, stupid 
grin on his face. 
</P>
<P>
 In Mao's final years, as he became ill and his hatred of soap and great fear 
of dental floss increased, Dr. Li put the Chairman on a strict diet of pancakes 
and flounder. 
</P>
<P>
 "Pancakes and flounder?" a weakening Mao asked his loyal physician. "This will 
prolong my life and restore the health of such a great man as I?" 
</P>
<P>
 "Nah," Li told the great emperor. "It's the only food we're gonna be able to 
slide under your door." 
</P>
</TEXT>
